## Method

::: callout-note
## Solving an IVP using the Laplace Transform

1.  Take the Laplace Transform

2.  Solve for $Y(s)=\mathscr{L}\{y(t)\}$

3.  Take the inverse Laplace Transform

$$\mathscr{L}^{-1}\{Y(s)\}=\mathscr{L}^{-1}\mathscr{L}\{y(t)\}=y(t)$$
:::

## Example {.scrollable}

::: {.callout-tip}
## Example
$$y'-4y=e^{3t},\qquad y(0)=1$$

::: {.callout-caution collapse="true"}
## Solution:

### 1.  Laplace Transform: {.unnumbered}

$$\mathscr{L}\{y'-4y\}=\mathscr{L}\{e^{3t}\}$$
$$\mathscr{L}\{y'\}-4\mathscr{L}\{y\}=\mathscr{L}\{e^{3t}\}$$
$$\boxed{sY(s)-y(0)-4Y(s)=\frac{1}{s-3}}$$  

### 2. Solve for $Y(s)$: {.unnumbered}

$$(s-4) Y(s)=\frac{1}{s-3}+1$$
$$Y(s)=\frac{1}{(s-3)(s-4)}+\frac{1}{(s-4)}$$
$$\text{Partial fractions}\cdots$$
$$\boxed{Y(s)=\frac{-1}{(s-3)}+\frac{2}{(s-4)}}$$


### 3. Inverse Laplace Transform :{.unnumbered}

$$y(t)=\mathscr{L}^{-1}\{Y(s)\}$$

$$y(t)=\mathscr{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{-1}{(s-3)}+\frac{2}{(s-4)}\right\}$$

$$\boxed{\boxed{y(t)=-e^{3t}+2e^{4t}}}$$
---

### Let's check:{.unnumbered}

$$y'-4y=e^{3t}$$

$$\mu(t)=e^{\int -4\,dt}=e^{-4t}$$

$$y(t)=\frac{1}{\mu(t)}\int \mu(t)Q(t)\,dt$$

$$=e^{4t}\int e^{-t}\,dt$$

$$y(t)=e^{4t}(-e^{-t}+C)$$

$$y(0)=(-1+C)=1\Rightarrow \boxed{C=2}$$

### We get the same!{.unnumbered}

$$y(t)=e^{4t}(-e^{-t}+2)$$

$$\boxed{y(t)=-e^{3t}+2e^{4t}}$$
:::
